org.jimmutable.core.fields

Class FieldConcurrentHashSet<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jimmutable.core.fields.FieldCollection<E>
      • org.jimmutable.core.fields.FieldSet<E>
        • org.jimmutable.core.fields.FieldConcurrentHashSet<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - The type of elements in this list
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Set<E>, Field

    public final class FieldConcurrentHashSet<E>
extends FieldSet<E>
    An implementation of a Set wrapper around ConcurrentHashMap (Collections.newSetFromMap(java.util.Map)) that begins life as mutable but can, at any time, be "frozen" (made immutable). In other words, a wrapper for a concurrent Set that implements Field.

    Why does one need a thread safe immutable set? Well... if your construction code (when the object is mutable) is threaded then it is much safer to use a concurrent backing store. In Java, it is nigh impossible to guarantee the mutable -> immutable transition in a multi-threaded context absent a concurrent backing store.

    In general, however (when the field is being created in single threaded code), just use FieldHashSet, which is far faster to construct.

    Author:
    Jim Kane
    See Also:
    FieldSet, FieldHashSet
